I am using the [app-module-path package](https://www.npmjs.com/package/app-module-path) in my app, and there is something I'd love to be able to configure in jsconfig.json so I can navigate between files more easily.

Consider this structure:

``` js
// a/foo.js
require('app-module-path').addPath(process.cwd());

var bar = require('b/bar')

bar()

// b/bar.js
module.exports = function () { console.log('bar') }
```

``` bash
$ node a/foo.js
"bar"
```

Unfortunately hovering `require('b/bar')` or CMD+Click on `b/bar` doesn't open b/bar.js.

Is there a way we could enter these kinds of re-mapped paths in jsconfig.json (or other)?

- VSCode Version: 1.3.1
- OS Version: Windows 10

Steps to Reproduce:
- Create a completion provide that always returns null (the docs say this is valid to signal no matching results)

```
provideCompletionItems(document: TextDocument, position: Position, token: CancellationToken): Thenable<CompletionList> {
    return new Promise<CompletionList>((resolve, reject) => {
        resolve(null);
    });
}
```
- Open a document that contains `import "` and invoke completion at the end of the line

The completion popup will show "import" which doesn't seem to make much sense. Selecting this will leave you with `import "import` which is obviously not useful. I would expect when there are no results the popup would not show, or would indicate that there are no suggestions.

Note: My example was "import", but the same thing happens with anything - you get the first previous text appearing in the popup.

![completion](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1078012/17381546/5b9b6c8c-59c4-11e6-8809-8789a6d90aa9.png)

- VSCode Version: 1.3.1 
- OS Version: OS X El Capitan

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Enter the following code

```
export class TestGeneric<T> { }
export class TestClass {
  someFunction():
    TestGeneric<string> {
    let a = 2;// syntax highlighting broken here
    return new TestGeneric<string>();
  }
}
```
1. Or the following code:

```
export class TestGeneric<T> { }
export class TestClass {
  someFunction
    ():TestGeneric<string> {
    let a = 2;// syntax highlighting broken here
    return new TestGeneric<string>();
  }
}
```

Also note that other syntax highlighting bugs have been noticed following that first bit of wierdness, but I have a hard time reproducing those with simple code. I think once the initial bug occurs text below that can randomly have issues.

- VSCode Version: 1.3.1
- OS Version: Windows 2012 R2

Steps to Reproduce:

``` ts
function foo () {
  let a = 0;
}

function boo() {
  let b = 0;
  let c = 0;
}
```
- Fold `boo()`
- Select `let` on `foo()`
- Ctrl-D, Ctrl-D
- Type 'const`(i.e. replace`let`with`const`
- Unfold `boo()`

You will see the code becomes:

``` ts

function foo () {
  const a = 0;
}

function boo() {
  const c = 0;
}
```

instead of 

``` ts
function foo () {
  const a = 0;
}

function boo() {
  const b = 0;
  const c = 0;
}
```

- VSCode Version: 1.4.0-insider (is there an easy way to copy-paste the full version number?)
- OS Version: Windows 7 x64

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Open a .less file
2. Write something like

``` less
.foo{
    @import "bar";
}
```

It's a valid syntax in LESS, but VS Code thinks it's an error.

See also https://github.com/less/less.js/issues/656
